<div id="middlecolumn1"><div class="multipageheading"><h1>Welcome to&nbsp;<strong>Policing and Public Safety</strong></h1><div class="multipagegraphic"><img width="70" height="70" src="/shared/graphics/kmbc/images/policing.gif" alt="Logotype for Policing and Public Safety" /></div>
</div>
<h2 class="subhead">Action plan orders</h2><div style="clear:both;">The aim of the Action Plan Order is to 
prevent you from further offending by 
working with you to deal with 
problems, which may have led you to 
get into trouble. It is a sentence of 
the court, which is supervised by a 
member of the Knowsley Youth Offending 
Team.<br />
<br />
</div>
<div style="clear:both;"><h2>What will I have to do?</h2>The court has ordered you to complete 
and Action Plan Order over the next 
three months. The content of the Order 
will vary for each young person. It 
may include some of the following 
elements after your needs have been 
assessed.<br />
<br />
</div>
<div style="clear:both;"><ul><li>You will see your youth offending team 
officer twice a week </li>
<li>You will be expected to do something 
to help the victim of your offence. 
This is called &#039;reparation&#039; and could 
be anything from writing a letter to 
say sorry, to more practical work. It 
may be that you will be found more 
general reparation work to help the 
community </li>
<li>You may receive sessions to help with 
health issues, for instance, drugs and 
alcohol, or help with education </li>
<li>The court may ask that you return 
after 21 days to review the progress 
of the order </li>
<li>You may go to an attendance centre to 
do two hours of activities once a 
fortnight </li>
<li>You will be expected to attend 
sessions to address your offending; 
this may be as part of a group </li>
<li>You may be told to keep away from a 
particular place or places </li>
<li>You may be required to keep to any 
plan, which has been put together for 
your education </li>
<li>You may be required to report to a 
particular place each week</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div style="clear:both;"><h2>What are the rules?</h2>You must keep all appointments given 
to you by the Youth Offending Team 
Officer and inform him/her of any 
change of address. You must allow your 
officer to see you at home if required 
and do the things that are set for you 
in your Action Plan Programme.<br />
<br />
If you do not keep to the rules, your 
officer will ask you for an 
explanation and they will decide if 
your reason is acceptable or not. If 
you fail to keep more than two 
appointments without an acceptable 
reason, you will be taken back to 
court.<br />
<br />
</div>
<div style="clear:both;"><h2>What if I have problems with the programme?</h2>We want your Action Plan to succeed. If you have any problems with attendance or other problems in completing the Order, let your officer know as soon as possible.<br />
<br />
If you do not co-operate with the Action Plan Order, you will be returned to the court and the court may:<br />
<br />
</div>
<div style="clear:both;"><ul><li>Order you to complete the Order </li>
<li>Fine you up to &pound;1000 </li>
<li>Impose an Attendance Centre Order </li>
<li>Discharge the Order and sentence you in a different way for the original offence </li>
<li>If your Action Plan Order was made in the Crown Court, you may be committed back to the Crown Court for re-sentence</li>
</ul>
</div>
